ariant of   Boye  .","Americanized form of French   Bois  ."]},{"name":"Bey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammed, Abdullah, Dawoud, Fatima, Jamaal, Rasheedah, Shakoor, Zaib, Aisha, Akil, Ameen, Aminah.","North German and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Beye</i> or <i>Baye</i>, vowel variants of   Boye  .","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Baj</b>: nickname or occupational name from Upper Sorbian <i>baj</i> ‘storyteller’. Compare   Bay  ."]},{"name":"Boje","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Goetz, Johannes.","German: variant of   Boye  ."]},{"name":"Boyens","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Georg.","North German and North Frisian: patronymic from the personal name   Boye  ."]},{"name":"Boy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans Peter, Heinz, Horst.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Boie</i>, which may be from ancient Germanic <i>Boio</i> (see   Boye   1 and 2) or an Old English <i>Boia</i>. The latter is common as a first element in English placenames, and is difficult to tell apart from the ordinary word <i>boy</i>, to which it may be related.","English: from Middle English <i>boy</i> ‘young man, servant’, also ‘knave’ or ‘rogue’. Compare   Ladd  ."]},{"name":"Boykins","meanings":["Americanized form of Dutch <b>Boeijkens</b>: patronymic from the personal name   Boye   with the diminutive element <i>-ken</i> and genitive <i>-s</i>. Compare the English cognate   Boykin   and North German   Boyken  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":14,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":39,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes 